snippet: The government said 209,000 jobs were created in July, while economists had expected about 230,000. The unemployment rate inched up to 6.2 percent.
abstract: Labor Department reports its estimate that United States economy added 209,000 jobs in July, with unemployment rate reaching 6.2 percent; report follows trend of strong pace of job creation over six-month period since 2006; numbers may pressure Federal Reserve to start raising interest rates sooner than anticipated.

byline.contributor: Binyamin Appelbaum and Neil Irwin contributed reporting.

lead_paragraph: The government said 209,000 jobs were created in July, while economists had expected about 230,000. The unemployment rate inched up to 6.2 percent.

headline.main: More Rejoin Labor Force; Jobless Rate Up to 6.2%
headline.print_headline: More Rejoin Labor Force; Jobless Rate Up to 6.2%
